A river that runs through northern Nevada in the western United States. It has no outlet to the ocean, but instead empties into the Humboldt Sink. The source of the river is a spring called Humboldt Wells at the northern tip of the East Humboldt Range, just outside the city of Wells. The river flows west-southwest through Elko County past the community of Elko. In northern Eureka County it passes along the south end of the Tuscarora Mountains, and then along the north end of the Shoshone Range. At Battle Mountain it turns northwest for approximately 80 km then west at Red House and past Golconda and a spur of the Sonoma Range. Then it turns southwest, flowing past Winnemuca and through Pershing County, along the western side of the Humboldt Range and the West Humboldt Range. It empties into an intermittent lake in the Humboldt Sink on the border between Pershing and Churchill counties, approximately 32 km southwest of Lovelock.

A river, approximately 450 km long, in southwestern Utah in the United States. It rises in northwestern Kane County along the western side of the Paunsaugunt Plateau, and flows northward into Garfield County through an extended valley beside the plateau past Hatch and Panguitch. Along the Garfield-Piute county line it descends through the narrow 8 km Circleville Canyon, emerging into a second valley southwest of Junction, where it receives the East Fork from the east and passes through the Piute Reservoir. It flows north across Piute County to Marysvale then descends through 13 km Sevier Canyon, emerging south of Sevier. It then flows northeast past Richfield and Salina. Approximately 32 km southwest of Nephi it turns west, flowing around the north end of the Canyon Mountains into the Sevier Desert, flowing southwest past Delta and into Sevier Lake in central Millard County, along the western side of the Cricket Mountains.

An 29 km river located in eastern Utah, United States. Its headwaters are located in the Wasatch Mountains of the western Uintah Basin. The river flows east into Strawberry Reservoir, and then out through Soldier Creek Dam. Below Soldier Creek Dam the river runs by the Strawberry Pinnacles where it is joined by the tributaries Avintaquin Creek and Red Creek. The narrow canyon that the river runs through is characterized by high steep cliffs and dense foliage. The river ends when it joins the Duchesne river east of the town of Duchesne, Utah.

A river in southwest Missouri. It is 172 km long, with headwaters in Lawrence and Greene counties; the headweaters join near Greenfield, then flow north through the Ozarks, to the Osage River, ending just above Osceola, Missouri in Truman Reservoir. Large portions of the Sac River and the Little Sac River are inundated by Stockton Lake.

A river that lows for 669 km through east Texas to its mouth on Sabine Lake near the Rainbow Bridge. Two major reservoirs, Lake Palestine and Lake B. A. Steinhagen are located on the Neches.

A river. A tributary of the Lower Mississippi River. The river is 188 miles long and is formed by the confluence of the Tallahatchie River and the Yalobusha River in Greenwood. The river parallels the Mississippi River for some distance before joining it north of Vicksburg, Mississippi. Natural levees which flank the Mississippi prevent the Yazoo from joining it before Vicksburg.
